    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-01-09T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-01-09T23:00:00-05:00" n="645"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d645">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">693.002/441: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-01-10T12:00:00+08:00"
                            >January 10, 1938—noon.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 4:11 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>48. Reference my telegram No. 45, January 9, 11 a.m. At a meeting this morning
                    the British Chargé d’Affaires said that his instructions had been to advise the
                    Inspector General to keep his Embassy <pb facs="0634" n="630" xml:id="pg_630"/>
                    fully informed and follow its advice and the Embassy would give him such support
                    as possible. French Ambassador has no instructions but is seeking them along
                    similar lines. Both diplomatic representatives are informing their Governments
                    of the purport of the statement communicated to you by my No. 45.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Hankow and Peiping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
